  "prompt": "What is Electromagnetic spectrum?",
  "response": "The electromagnetic spectrum is the entire range of electromagnetic radiation. Electromagnetic radiation is a form of energy that travels in waves and has both electric and magnetic field components. It encompasses all types of light, from radio waves to gamma rays, differing in their frequency and wavelength.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **What it is:** A continuous spectrum of all possible electromagnetic radiation.\n*   **What it includes:** Radio waves, microwaves, infrared, visible light, ultraviolet, X-rays, and gamma rays.\n*   **Key characteristics:** Electromagnetic radiation is characterized by its frequency (how many wave cycles pass a point per second), wavelength (the distance between successive crests of a wave), and energy (directly proportional to frequency).\n*   **Arrangement:** The spectrum is arranged in order of increasing frequency (and decreasing wavelength). So, radio waves have the lowest frequency and longest wavelength, while gamma rays have the highest frequency and shortest wavelength.\n*   **How it travels:** Electromagnetic radiation travels at the speed of light in a vacuum.\n*   **Applications:** Different parts of the electromagnetic spectrum have different applications, from communication (radio waves, microwaves) to medical imaging (X-rays) to sterilization (ultraviolet light).\n\n**In simpler terms:**\n\nImagine a rainbow, but instead of just the colors we can see (visible light), it includes all the other \"colors\" of light that our eyes can't detect. The electromagnetic spectrum is that entire rainbow, from the longest waves (radio) to the shortest waves (gamma).\n\n**Here's a table summarizing the major regions of the electromagnetic spectrum:**\n\n| Region          | Wavelength                      | Frequency                    | Energy      | Common Uses                                                                      |\n|-----------------|---------------------------------|------------------------------|-------------|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| Radio Waves     | > 1 mm                          | < 300 GHz                    | Low         | Communication (radio, TV), radar, navigation                                     |\n| Microwaves      | 1 mm - 1 m                      | 300 MHz - 300 GHz           | Low         | Cooking, communication (cell phones, satellite), radar                               |\n| Infrared        | 700 nm - 1 mm                   | 300 GHz - 430 THz           | Medium      | Heat detection, remote controls, thermal imaging                                  |\n| Visible Light   | 400 nm - 700 nm                 | 430 THz - 750 THz           | Medium      | Human vision, photography, illumination                                           |\n| Ultraviolet     | 10 nm - 400 nm                  | 750 THz - 30 PHz             | High        | Sterilization, tanning, vitamin D production, some medical treatments             |\n| X-rays          | 0.01 nm - 10 nm                 | 30 PHz - 30 EHz              | High        | Medical imaging, security scanning, crystallography                                  |\n| Gamma Rays      | < 0.01 nm                       | > 30 EHz                     | Very High   | Cancer treatment, sterilization, nuclear medicine, astronomy                         |\n\nThe electromagnetic spectrum is fundamental to our understanding of the universe and has countless applications in science, technology, and everyday life.\n",
